        "id": 1993490,
        "name": null,
        "username": "jbray23",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/j/e79b87/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2016-08-16T05:18:50.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>The 15\u2019s just hit Seattle so I decided to grab a couple of bottles of Breze and a bottle of Les Moulins. I bought the three because I never see the Breze and since there were a couple cases of les Moulins I could give it a go and decided if I wanted more.</p>\n<p>15\u2019 from my understanding is a ripe vintage, not over ripe but phenolically ripe\u2026</p>\n<p>Popped this wine and drank Half the bottle saving the last for tomorrow, opened for about 5 hours total from 1st glass to the last\u2026</p>\n<p>Nose was intense stones with peach, really clean and reminded me of a perfectly ripe Sauv blanc. Melon, chalk, lemon, round mouthfeel with a devastating acidic cut which is where my question mark comes from.</p>\n<p>Those with experience of older vintages of Guibertreau a question for you, does this acid integrate?  I love the bones of this wine, but man, this is sharp, even in a ripe vintage, does that faint peach fruit come to the front and age into a fantastic beast?</p>\n<p>I\u2019m almost ready to buy a couple of cases and from what the guys who I bought this from say, the reds are even better. Im hesitant based on that lean acid and would love input from people who\u2019ve seen the holy grail.</p>\n<p>People with experience, thoughts?</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 2,
